<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Words Ending With -ED — Scrabble Suffix Scoring Guide</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 5 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">The -ED suffix is Scrabble's most universal ending. Nearly every verb accepts it, creating over 5000 valid words. While E and D together add just 3 points, the strategic value is immense — you can extend existing board words, form parallel plays, and access past-tense forms of power-tile verbs like QUIZZED and OXIDIZED.</p>

<p>The key with -ED isn't finding words — it's knowing when to use it versus saving those common tiles for higher-scoring independent plays.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Why -ED Matters in Scrabble</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">E(1)+D(2) base</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">5000+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid -ED words</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3–15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letter length range</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>E is the most common tile (12 in the bag) and D appears 4 times. You'll frequently have ED available. The skill isn't finding -ED words — it's knowing when to play them versus saving those tiles for something bigger.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Top Scoring -ED Words</h2>

